Organization = {{Int Inst Informat Syst; Inter Amer Org Higher Educ; IEEE Comp Soc,
   Venezuela Chapter}},
Abstract = {{This paper describes architecture of a simulation-supported Enterprise
   Resource Planning (ERP) system to provide engineers, managers, and
   business professionals with an interactive, dynamic, and enterprise-wide
   training and learning model. Such model aims at presenting key business
   functions in an organization in a consolidated and highly efficient and
   streamlined structure to be used for practicing enterprise modeling,
   analysis, and decision-making. Segmental training on standalone business
   functions will not provide trainee with a comprehensive and integral
   understanding of the coherency and synergy among different business
   function. Such vision is necessary to prepare successful business
   leaders and partners as an essential for prosperity in today's
   marketplace. Thus, and in addition to its critical operational
   functionality, ERP system can be utilized for enterprise-wide training
   and learning since it represents the practice consolidating of an
   enterprise's planning, manufacturing, and sales and marketing efforts
   into an integrated management and control system. As a core function in
   its business structure, an enterprise production system is often the
   primary driver of the performance of other business-supporting functions
   such as finance, sales, and distribution. The complexity and stochastic
   and dynamic nature of the enterprise production system, however, often
   limits the training and learning capability of an ERP system especially
   in understanding and practicing the actual dynamics of production
   activities and their interaction with other business functions.
   Therefore, a Simulation Module (SM), representing the underlying
   production system, is proposed as an interactive add-in module into a
   company's ERP system to compensate for such limitation towards better
   and more effective enterprise-wide training and learning. Training
   examples are presented to demonstrate the SM functionality into the ERP
   system.}},
