Abstract = {{Enterprise Engineering and Integration, especially in the new
   environments of extended and virtual enterprises can be very efficiently
   supported by business process modelling (BPM). BPM can enable simulation
   of what-if scenarios, provide enhanced decision support based on real
   time operation monitoring, and can be employed for the control of
   enterprise assets. It may serve to prepare user requirements and to
   design of integrated information systems, like ERP (Enterprise Resource
   Planning). However, with many dissimilar modelling methodologies
   available, the selection of the most suited one becomes a very difficult
   task. Most modelling methodologies follow the life-cycle concept, but
   usually cover only the early phases, namely requirements definition and
   design specification. In addition, diverging terminology and different
   modelling language constructs used for the representation of the model
   are further obstacles to selecting most appropriate model based
   solution.
   Starting from the CIMOSA architecture, the paper investigates and
   compares modelling constructs of selected, BPM methodologies, using the
   draft standard ``Constructs for Enterprise Modelling{''} (EN ISO 19440,
   2002) as a reference. Further, examples of user oriented construct types
   and an overview of icon types for graphical representation are
   presented. User requirements for improved BPM methodologies, construct
   types and tool interfaces are derived and discussed which will help to
   improve common understanding, acceptance and deployment of the
   technologies. The paper will serve to harmonise future user requirements
   and case the design of interfaces between modelling tools, as outlined
   in the UEML project. Finally, the impact and benefits of standards in
   this context are briefly discussed. Only with increased efforts in
   harmonisation and standardisation, will the envisaged potential
   improvements of business process modelling be realised.}},
